---
import ServiceLayout from '../../layouts/ServiceLayout.astro';

const title = 'E-commerce website development';
const description =
  'Online stores that convert. Apriori Studio builds Shopify, WooCommerce, and fully custom storefronts — with payments, inventory, and fast checkout that works on every device.';
---

<ServiceLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  serviceType="E-commerce website development"
  breadcrumbs={[
    { href: '/', label: 'Home' },
    { href: '/web', label: 'Websites' },
    { href: '/web/ecommerce', label: 'E-commerce stores' },
  ]}
>
  <p>
    Selling online is a category of website where small details add up to big revenue swings.
    A checkout that takes one extra step. A product image that loads slowly on mobile. An email
    receipt that ends up in spam. A search box that misses obvious matches. Each of these,
    individually, costs you a few percent of sales — and they compound. We build e-commerce sites
    with that compounding effect in mind, so the small things are right by default.
  </p>

  <h2>What we build</h2>
  <p>
    Most stores fit one of three shapes, and we work in all of them. For under a few hundred
    products with standard payment and shipping needs, <strong>Shopify</strong> is usually the
    right call — fast to launch, low maintenance, well-supported. For more flexibility on
    integrations and a lower long-term running cost, <strong>WooCommerce</strong> on a VPS is
    a strong fit. For unusual product models (subscriptions with custom pricing logic, B2B
    quotation flows, marketplaces with multiple sellers), a <strong>custom storefront</strong>
    with a headless commerce backend gives you the room to do things off the shelf can't.
  </p>
  <p>
    We won't push you into a custom build if Shopify will do. We won't push you into Shopify if
    your business model needs a custom build. We'll tell you the trade-offs of each, including
    what they cost to run year-on-year.
  </p>

  <h2>End-to-end, not just code</h2>

  <h3>Domain and email setup</h3>
  <p>
    We register your domain through a registrar that gives you proper control (and won't trap
    you with renewal price hikes). We configure email-related DNS records — SPF, DKIM, DMARC —
    so order confirmations and shipping updates don't land in junk folders, which kills more
    repeat business than people realise.
  </p>

  <h3>Hosting that scales with you</h3>
  <p>
    For a Shopify store you don't think about hosting — that's part of the appeal. For
    WooCommerce or custom stores, we pick a VPS or managed host that fits your traffic profile,
    with caching (Redis, Varnish, or CDN-level) so the storefront stays fast even during a
    promotion. We set up automated backups, SSL renewal, and monitoring so you find out about
    issues before customers do.
  </p>

  <h3>Design and storefront UX</h3>
  <p>
    We design for one purpose: helping a visitor become a buyer without friction. That means
    fast-loading product pages with images that don't jump as they load, clear pricing and
    delivery info above the fold, a one-page checkout with guest option, mobile-first everything.
    We test on real phones, not just Chrome dev tools.
  </p>

  <h3>Payments and integrations</h3>
  <p>
    Stripe, PayPal, Apple Pay, Google Pay, Klarna for buy-now-pay-later, GoCardless for
    direct debit. Shipping integrations (Royal Mail, DPD, Evri, ShipStation, Sendcloud).
    Accounting (Xero, QuickBooks, FreshBooks). Email marketing (Klaviyo, MailChimp,
    SendGrid). Reviews (Trustpilot, Yotpo, Judge.me). Analytics (Google Analytics 4,
    Plausible, Fathom). We've connected most of these before — and we'll only set up the
    ones you actually need at your stage.
  </p>

  <h3>Search, filters, and recommendations</h3>
  <p>
    On a small catalogue, the built-in search is usually fine. Past a few hundred SKUs, native
    search starts missing things and customers leave. We add proper search (Algolia, Meilisearch,
    or Manticore depending on budget) with synonyms, typo tolerance, and faceted filtering.
    Cross-sell and upsell modules where they make sense, not where they annoy.
  </p>

  <h3>Inventory, orders, and admin</h3>
  <p>
    Whether your stock lives in Shopify, WooCommerce, or a separate ERP, we wire it up so your
    storefront shows accurate availability and your order flow updates the right systems.
    For multi-channel sellers (your store + Amazon + eBay + a physical till), we'll set up
    inventory sync so you don't oversell.
  </p>

  <h3>Tax, GDPR, and compliance</h3>
  <p>
    UK VAT, EU OSS thresholds, US sales tax via TaxJar or Avalara — we configure the right
    setup for where you sell. Cookie consent banner that actually meets the GDPR requirement
    (not just a "got it" button). Privacy policy and terms of service templates we'll tailor to
    your business.
  </p>

  <h2>What it costs</h2>
  <p>
    A small Shopify store with standard payment, shipping and design (under 100 products, no
    custom integrations) typically lands at £4,000 to £8,000, including theme customisation and
    copywriting support. A WooCommerce store of similar scope is roughly the same range. A
    custom-built storefront for an unusual business model starts at £10,000 and is quoted
    per-project. Hosting, payment processor fees, and any third-party SaaS subscriptions are
    yours to pay directly — we don't mark those up.
  </p>

  <h2>How long it takes</h2>
  <p>
    Most small-to-medium e-commerce builds take six to ten weeks from kickoff to launch,
    assuming you have product photos, copy, and brand assets ready (or know what you want from
    them). Larger custom builds run twelve to twenty weeks. We share a written timeline with
    each project so you know what's happening when.
  </p>

  <h2>After launch</h2>
  <p>
    Going live is the start. We monitor uptime, keep your platform and plugins up to date,
    apply security patches, and back up your store on a schedule. If you hit a sales spike,
    we scale your hosting before it falls over. If you want a new feature in three months, we
    quote it and ship it. If you want to take everything in-house, we hand it over cleanly with
    documentation — there's no lock-in.
  </p>
</ServiceLayout>
